.SH NAME
Element.setAttribute \- Element: setAttribute() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
Sets the value of an attribute on the specified element.
If the attribute already exists, the value is updated; otherwise a new
attribute is added with the specified name and value.
.PP
To get the current value of an attribute, use \f[CR]getAttribute()\f[R];
to remove an attribute, call \f[CR]removeAttribute()\f[R].
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
setAttribute(name, value)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]name\f[R]
A string specifying the name of the attribute whose value is to be set.
The attribute name is automatically converted to all lower\-case when
\f[CR]setAttribute()\f[R] is called on an HTML element in an HTML
document.
.TP
\f[B]value\f[R]
A string containing the value to assign to the attribute.
Any non\-string value specified is converted automatically into a
string.
.PP
Boolean attributes are considered to be \f[CR]true\f[R] if they\[cq]re
present on the element at all.
You should set \f[CR]value\f[R] to the empty string
(\f[CR]\[dq]\[dq]\f[R]) or the attribute\[cq]s name, with no leading or
trailing whitespace.
See the example below for a practical demonstration.
.PP
Since the specified \f[CR]value\f[R] gets converted into a string,
specifying \f[CR]null\f[R] doesn\[cq]t necessarily do what you expect.
Instead of removing the attribute or setting its value to be
\f[CR]null\f[R], it instead sets the attribute\[cq]s value to the string
\f[CR]\[dq]null\[dq]\f[R].
If you wish to remove an attribute, call \f[CR]removeAttribute()\f[R].
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]InvalidCharacterError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if the \f[CR]name\f[R] value is not a valid \c
.UR https://www.w3.org/TR/REC-xml/#dt-name
XML name
.UE \c
; for example, it starts with a number, a hyphen, or a period, or
contains characters other than alphanumeric characters, underscores,
hyphens, or periods.
.SH EXAMPLES
In the following example, \f[CR]setAttribute()\f[R] is used to set
attributes on a \f[CR]<button>\f[R].
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<button>Hello World</button>
.EE
.PP
\f[CR]css hidden button {   height: 30px;   width: 100px;   margin: 1em; }\f[R]
.SS JavaScript
.IP
.EX
const button = document.querySelector(\[dq]button\[dq]);

button.setAttribute(\[dq]name\[dq], \[dq]helloButton\[dq]);
button.setAttribute(\[dq]disabled\[dq], \[dq]\[dq]);
.EE
.PP
This demonstrates two things:
.IP \[bu] 2
The first call to \f[CR]setAttribute()\f[R] above shows changing the
\f[CR]name\f[R] attribute\[cq]s value to \[lq]helloButton\[rq].
