.IP \[bu] 2
To set the value of a Boolean attribute, such as \f[CR]disabled\f[R],
you can specify any value.
An empty string or the name of the attribute are recommended values.
All that matters is that if the attribute is present at all,
\f[I]regardless of its actual value\f[R], its value is considered to be
\f[CR]true\f[R].
The absence of the attribute means its value is \f[CR]false\f[R].
By setting the value of the \f[CR]disabled\f[R] attribute to the empty
string (\f[CR]\[dq]\[dq]\f[R]), we are setting \f[CR]disabled\f[R] to
\f[CR]true\f[R], which results in the button being disabled.
.SS Gecko notes
Using \f[CR]setAttribute()\f[R] to modify certain attributes, most
notably \f[CR]value\f[R] in XUL, works inconsistently, as the attribute
specifies the default value.
To access or modify the current values, you should use the properties.
For example, use \f[CR]Element.value\f[R] instead of
\f[CR]Element.setAttribute()\f[R].
